---
layout: article
title: Registration
description: Register your app for Sign in with Appwrite through the Console or the Apps API.
back: /docs/partners/apps
---

Your app appears on the consent screen as a registered client: a name, a logo, and a set of credentials tied to redirect URIs. Appwrite gives you two ways to register: the Console for people, the Apps API for code.

| Method | Best for | Credentials |
| --- | --- | --- |
| [Console](#console) | Products with a marketplace listing: a logo, legal pages, managed secrets | Client ID and secrets you manage |
| [Apps API](#apps-api) | The same apps, managed from code | Client ID and secrets you manage |

# Client types {% #client-types %}

Every client is `confidential` or `public`, and the choice decides how it authenticates.

- **Confidential** clients have a backend that keeps a secret. They authenticate token requests with the client secret, and their tokens live longer: 8 hours for access tokens and 365 days for refresh tokens by default.
- **Public** clients run where a secret cannot survive: single-page apps, native apps, CLIs. They carry no secret and must use [PKCE](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7636) with `S256` on every authorization. Their tokens default to 1 hour and 30 days.

Choose confidential whenever a server takes part in the flow. Public exists for the rest.

# Console {% #console %}

{% only_dark %}
![Marketplace tab of an organization showing the app catalog and the Add app action](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/registration-marketplace.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![Marketplace tab of an organization showing the app catalog and the Add app action](/images/docs/partners/apps/registration-marketplace.avif)
{% /only_light %}

Register through the Console when your app is a product: the same flow that creates the client also builds its marketplace listing. In your organization, open the **Marketplace** tab and click **Add app**. Give the app a name, a slug, a category, and a description. The slug becomes the app's client ID, and the app starts as a draft that only your organization sees.

The app's pages hold everything else, split across **General**, **OAuth client**, **OAuth secrets**, **Legal**, **Support**, and **Publish**.

## OAuth client {% #console-oauth-client %}

{% only_dark %}
![OAuth client settings with client type, device flow, and redirect URIs](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/registration-oauth-client.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![OAuth client settings with client type, device flow, and redirect URIs](/images/docs/partners/apps/registration-oauth-client.avif)
{% /only_light %}

The **OAuth client** page sets the protocol details: the [client type](#client-types), the device flow toggle for TVs and CLIs, and the redirect URIs. Add every URI your app returns to; the authorization endpoint rejects anything not on the list.

## OAuth secrets {% #console-oauth-secrets %}

{% only_dark %}
![OAuth secrets page listing an active secret with its hint](/images/docs/partners/apps/dark/registration-secrets.avif)
{% /only_dark %}
{% only_light %}
![OAuth secrets page listing an active secret with its hint](/images/docs/partners/apps/registration-secrets.avif)
{% /only_light %}

The **OAuth secrets** page issues client secrets for confidential apps. Each secret's value appears once, at creation; store it in your deployment environment before closing the dialog. The list keeps only a hint of each secret, its creation date, and when it was last used. See [Secrets](#secrets) for the rotation workflow.

## Publish {% #console-publish %}

**Legal** and **Support** hold the privacy policy, terms of service, data deletion, and contact details that the consent screen links. When the listing is complete, the **Publish** page makes the app visible in the marketplace catalog for every organization. Publishing changes discovery, not authorization: users consent to your app the same way whether it is a draft or published.

# Apps API {% #apps-api %}

Everything the Console does, the `apps` service does from code. Authenticate with your Appwrite account's session; the apps you create belong to you, or to a team you pass in `teamId`.

{% multicode %}
```server-nodejs
import { Client, Apps, ID } from 'node-appwrite';

const client = new Client()
    .setEndpoint('https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1')
    .setProject('console')
    .setSession(''); // Your Appwrite account session

const apps = new Apps(client);

const app = await apps.create({
    appId: ID.unique(),
    name: 'Horizon',
    redirectUris: ['https://horizon.example.com/oauth/callback'],
    description: 'Deployment dashboard for your Appwrite projects.',
    tagline: 'Ship from one place',
    logoUri: 'https://horizon.example.com/logo.png',
    clientUri: 'https://horizon.example.com',
    privacyPolicyUrl: 'https://horizon.example.com/privacy',
    termsUrl: 'https://horizon.example.com/terms',
    type: 'confidential'
});
```

