```server-go
package main

import (
    "fmt"

    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/apps"
    "github.com/appwrite/sdk-for-go/client"
)

func main() {
    c := client.New(
        client.WithEndpoint("https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1"),
        client.WithProject("console"),
        client.WithSession(""), // Your Appwrite account session
    )

    service := apps.New(c)

    secret, err := service.CreateSecret("<APP_ID>")
    if err != nil {
        panic(err)
    }

    fmt.Println(secret)
}
```

```server-rust
use appwrite::Client;
use appwrite::services::Apps;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
    let client = Client::new();
    client.set_endpoint("https://cloud.appwrite.io/v1");
    client.set_project("console");
    client.set_session(""); // Your Appwrite account session

    let apps = Apps::new(&client);

    let secret = apps.create_secret("<APP_ID>").await?;
    println!("{}", secret.secret); // Shown only once

    Ok(())
}
```
{% /multicode %}

An app holds several active secrets at once, so rotation needs no downtime: create a new secret, deploy it, then delete the old one. Each stored secret keeps a `hint` (its last characters), who created it, and when it was last used, which tells you when the old secret is safe to delete.

Two more operations matter over an app's life. `updateTeam` moves ownership to a team, so registration does not depend on one person's account. `deleteTokens` is the kill switch: it invalidates every token the app has been issued, for every user.

# Labels {% #labels %}

Labels such as `official` and `partner` mark apps the platform vouches for, and consent screens surface them as trust signals. Labels are assigned by Appwrite, not by the app itself, so they cannot be self-granted. Contact your partner manager to have your app labeled.
